  abstract = {Pebble bed reactors (PBRs) are expected to display excellent heat removal characteristics due to graphite's capability for storing and transferring heat, the high failure temperatures of particle fuel, and the low power densities involved. However, a major challenge associated with the modeling of PBRs is the complex fuel-coolant structure in the core. Thermalhydraulic (T/H) modeling of PBRs requires consideration of thermal and  ow e{\enspace}ects over {\enspace}ve orders in spatial magnitude{\textbar}from 109 fuel particles, each about 1 mm in size, to 5{\enspace}105 pebbles, each about 5 cm in size, within a 10 m-size reactor core in the larger context of a power generating system. This research develops and applies multiscale methods to the thermal analysis of PBRs. By decomposing the complex PBR geometry into coupled models for three characteristic length scales{\textbar}the particle, pebble, and core{\textbar}e{\enspace}cient predictions of core T/H relevant to reactor design are achieved. These multiscale models are implemented in a new {\enspace}nite element software application built on the open source Multiphysics Object-Oriented Software Environment (MOOSE). By leveraging state-of-the-art numerical methods, solvers, and meshing tools, this dissertation enables rapid design and analysis for scoping studies, fast-turnaround design, and multiphysics cou2 pling to a comprehensive reactor analysis framework. Application of multiscale analysis to a wide variety of  ows demonstrates the software tool's capabilities as a general  ow solver and the applicability of these models to both porous and open  ows. Veri{\enspace}cation for open  ows shows that the multiscale model reduces to the Navier-Stokes equations in regions such as reactor plena, where prediction of mixing and the ensuing thermal stresses are essential to the design of reactor internals. Application to the SANA experiments, a gas-cooled scaled PBR facility, demonstrates that the multiscale model predicts the passive conduction cool-down heat removal process with an average solid temperature error of 22.6{\enspace}C. Statistical analysis as a function of position within the bed and other experimental characteristics highlights limitations of model closures and simpli{\enspace}cations that are useful in guiding further macroscale analysis of gas-cooled PBRs. Supported by the veri{\enspace}cation and validation for open  ows and gas systems, full-core steadystate T/H analysis is performed for the Mark-1 Pebble Bed Fluoride-Salt-Cooled High- Temperature Reactor (PB-FHR). The unconventional re ector block design, uniquely thin fuel-matrix annulus, and non-uniform  ow boundary conditions (BCs) highlight the new capabilities enabled by this research for PBR industrial analysis. Two multiscale fuel models are compared against full-resolved PB-FHR fuel pebbles for a wide range in thermal conditions. While a homogeneous layer model is characterized by errors in excess of 200{\enspace}C, a linear superposition method is shown to predict average and maximum temperatures to within 10{\enspace}C. Early models of PBRs have struggled to accurately characterize the core bypass fraction, with signi{\enspace}cant implications on fuel temperature predictions. A porous media model is constructed of the re ectors corresponding to the maximum-bypass end-of-life condition with friction factor correlations generated using COMSOL Multiphysics. A tensor representation of the friction factor shows that the momentum loss is signi{\enspace}cantly higher in the radial than the axial direction. These drag models are combined with the multiscale fuel veri{\enspace}cation for full-core analysis of the PB-FHR. A parametric study varying the re ector block gap distribution and the in ow port design demonstrates that the in ow BC has a signi{\enspace}cant e{\enspace}ect on the core bypass fraction and that the bypass fraction is a strong function of the re ector block gap distribution. The maximum bypass fraction is predicted to be within the range of 11.9\%\{14.0\% depending on the in ow BC and gap distribution. For a bottomheavy center re ector inlet, fuel and re ector temperature predictions are provided. The primary e{\enspace}ect of the core bypass is to uniformly raise core temperatures; for all re ector 3 gap distributions, the maximum kernel temperature is approximately 93{\enspace}C higher than the maximum  uid temperature, which remains far below the fuel failure limit. This work demonstrates the utility of multiscale methods to thermal analysis of PBRs. In conjunction with the larger scienti{\enspace}c community, this research enables fast-turnaround design and analysis of all single-phase PBRs to facilitate the contribution of advanced nuclear reactors to a clean energy future.\vphantom\}},
